<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SNP Detection Methods in Staphylococcus aureus Research</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

<script>
(function() {
    'use strict';

    function initTheme() {
        const filename = location.pathname.split('/').pop().replace('.html', '') || 'default';
        
        let seed = 0;
        
        // Mix all character codes into the seed with prime multipliers
        for (let i = 0; i < filename.length; i++) {
            seed += filename.charCodeAt(i) * (31 + (i % 7));
        }

        // Extract year if any (4-digit number in filename)
        const yearMatch = filename.match(/\d{4}/);
        if (yearMatch) {
            seed += parseInt(yearMatch[0]) * 13;
        }

        // Further mix with golden ratio to scatter more
        seed = Math.floor((seed * 0.6180339887) % 1 * 10000);

        const themeNumber = (seed % 30) + 1; // Result: 1 to 30

        document.body.setAttribute('data-theme', 'auto-' + themeNumber);
        if (yearMatch) {
            document.body.setAttribute('data-year', yearMatch[0]);
        }
    }

    function initBackToTop() {
        const btn = document.createElement('div');
        btn.className = 'back-to-top';
        btn.setAttribute('aria-label', 'Back to top');
        btn.onclick = () => window.scrollTo({top: 0, behavior: 'smooth'});
        document.body.appendChild(btn);
        
        window.onscroll = () => {
            btn.classList.toggle('visible', window.pageYOffset > 300);
        };
    }

    document.readyState === 'loading'
        ? document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {initTheme(); initBackToTop();})
        : (initTheme(), initBackToTop());
})();
</script>

</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <!-- TOP LEFT NAVIGATION -->
        <div class="top-left-nav">
            <a href="../index.html">Back to Index</a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="header">
            <h1>SNP Detection Methods and Applications in Staphylococcus aureus Research</h1>
            <p>Comprehensive Review of Methodologies and Clinical Applications</p>
            
            <div class="header-info">
                <p class="text-small"><strong>Authors:</strong> Ying Jian, Min Li</p>
                <p class="text-small text-top"><strong>Institution:</strong> Department of Laboratory Medicine, Shanghai Jiao Tong University School of Medicine Affiliated Renji Hospital, Shanghai, China</p>
                <p class="text-small text-top"><strong>Journal:</strong> Journal of Bio-X Research (2021) 4:1–9</p>
                <p class="text-top-large">
                    <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/JBR.0000000000000071"
                       target="_blank" 
                       class="paper-link">
                         View Original Paper
                    </a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="content">
            <div class="section" id="section-overview">
                <div class="section-title">Paper Overview & Context</div>
                
                <div class="citation-box">
                    <p><strong>Citation:</strong> Jian, Y., & Li, M. (2021). A narrative review of single-nucleotide polymorphism detection methods and their application in studies of Staphylococcus aureus. Journal of Bio-X Research, 4(1), 1-9.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>Review Focus:</strong> Comprehensive analysis of SNP detection methodologies and their practical applications in S. aureus epidemiological and clinical research.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>Clinical Significance:</strong> S. aureus accounts for ~9.3% of clinical infections in China (2019) and represents the third-ranked pathogen overall, making SNP-based tracking and resistance monitoring critically important.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="innovation-box">
                    <div class="innovation-title">Key Innovation: Bridging Technology and Clinical Application</div>
                    <p>This review uniquely connects advanced SNP detection technologies with real-world applications in S. aureus outbreak investigation, antimicrobial resistance tracking, and epidemiological surveillance - providing a practical framework for clinical microbiology laboratories.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section" id="section-analysis">
                <div class="section-title">Why, How, What Analysis</div>
                
                <div class="analysis-grid">
                    <div class="analysis-card why-card">
                        <div class="analysis-title">WHY - Clinical Need</div>
                        <div class="analysis-content">
                            <strong>Critical Problems:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">MRSA emergence</span> - Community-associated strains with enhanced virulence</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Multidrug resistance</span> - Limited treatment options for MDRSA</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Outbreak tracking</span> - Need for high-resolution epidemiological tools</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Hospital-acquired infections</span> - Transmission route identification</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>Why SNPs Matter:</strong>
                            <p>SNPs provide the highest resolution genetic markers for tracking S. aureus transmission, evolution, and resistance development - essential for modern infection control.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="analysis-card how-card">
                        <div class="analysis-title">HOW - Detection Technologies</div>
                        <div class="analysis-content">
                            <strong>Two Main Approaches:</strong>
                            
                            <div class="method-comparison">
                                <div class="method-box method-1">
                                    <div class="method-title">1. Whole Genome Sequencing (WGS)</div>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><strong>NGS Platforms:</strong> Illumina (most common), Ion Torrent, others</li>
                                        <li><strong>Workflow:</strong> DNA extraction → library prep → sequencing → bioinformatics</li>
                                        <li><strong>Tools:</strong> BWA, SAMtools, GATK pipeline</li>
                                        <li><strong>Output:</strong> Comprehensive SNP profiles across entire genome</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                                
                                <div class="method-box method-2">
                                    <div class="method-title">2. PCR-Based Methods</div>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><strong>Allele-Specific PCR (ASPCR):</strong> TaqMan probes for known SNPs</li>
                                        <li><strong>High-Resolution Melting (HRM):</strong> Detects unknown SNPs via Tm differences</li>
                                        <li><strong>Digital PCR:</strong> Single-molecule detection</li>
                                        <li><strong>COLD-PCR:</strong> Enhanced amplification of variants</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <strong>Alternative Methods:</strong>
                            <p>Mass spectrometry (MALDI-TOF-MS), SNP arrays, SNaPshot, DHPLC - each with specific advantages for targeted applications.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="analysis-card what-card">
                        <div class="analysis-title">WHAT - Clinical Applications</div>
                        <div class="analysis-content">
                            <strong>Epidemiological Applications:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Outbreak investigation</span> - Defining transmission chains</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Hospital surveillance</span> - Tracking nosocomial spread</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Community transmission</span> - USA300 household spread studies</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Global surveillance</span> - International clone tracking</li>
                            </ul>

                            <strong>Resistance Monitoring:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Daptomycin resistance</span> - rpoB, clpX, mprF mutations</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Vancomycin resistance</span> - VISA development pathways</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Linezolid resistance</span> - 23S rRNA mutations</li>
                            </ul>

                            <strong>Research Applications:</strong>
                            <p>Bacterial interactions, livestock-human transmission links, colonization vs. infection studies.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section" id="section-methods">
                <div class="section-title">SNP Detection Method Comparison</div>
                
                <div class="comparison-grid">
                    <div class="comparison-box">
                        <div class="comparison-title">Whole Genome Sequencing (NGS)</div>
                        <div class="step-details">
                            <strong>Strengths:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Comprehensive genome-wide SNP detection</li>
                                <li>De novo and resequencing capabilities</li>
                                <li>High throughput, multiple samples simultaneously</li>
                                <li>Detects all variant types (SNPs, indels, SVs)</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>Limitations:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Limited sensitivity in heterogeneous samples</li>
                                <li>Complex bioinformatics requirements</li>
                                <li>Challenges with repetitive genome regions</li>
                                <li>Higher cost for small-scale studies</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>Best for:</strong> Comprehensive outbreak investigations, unknown pathogen characterization
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="comparison-box">
                        <div class="comparison-title">Real-time PCR Methods</div>
                        <div class="step-details">
                            <strong>Strengths:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Rapid results (hours vs. days)</li>
                                <li>High sensitivity and specificity</li>
                                <li>Lower cost per sample</li>
                                <li>Established in most laboratories</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>Limitations:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Limited to known SNP sites</li>
                                <li>Lower throughput</li>
                                <li>Requires prior sequence knowledge</li>
                                <li>Multiple assays needed for comprehensive analysis</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>Best for:</strong> Routine surveillance, resistance gene detection, point-of-care testing
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="comparison-box">
                        <div class="comparison-title">Specialized Methods</div>
                        <div class="step-details">
                            <strong>Mass Spectrometry (MALDI-TOF-MS):</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>High multiplexing capability (30-50 SNPs)</li>
                                <li>Excellent accuracy and speed</li>
                                <li>Expensive equipment requirement</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>SNP Arrays:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>High-throughput, automated</li>
                                <li>Good for GWAS studies</li>
                                <li>Limited to known SNP positions</li>
                            </ul>
                            
                            <strong>SNaPshot:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Multiplex capability (up to 50 SNPs)</li>
                                <li>High sensitivity</li>
                                <li>Multi-step process, contamination risk</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section" id="section-applications">
                <div class="section-title">Clinical Application Examples</div>
                
                <div class="flow-container">
                    <div class="flow-step">
                        <div class="step-number">1</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <div class="step-title">Hospital Outbreak Investigation</div>
                            <div class="step-details">
                                <strong>Case Study:</strong> EMRSA-15 outbreak in Scotland
                                <div class="step-specs">
                                    <strong>Method:</strong> Whole-genome SNP analysis of 17 strains<br>
                                    <strong>Results:</strong> 904 total SNPs identified (723 strain-specific)<br>
                                    <strong>Discrimination:</strong> <25 SNPs = closely related transmission<br>
                                    <strong>Outcome:</strong> Rapid, reproducible outbreak tracking
                                </div>
                                <p><strong>Key Insight:</strong> SNP-based analysis provided superior discrimination compared to traditional typing methods.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="flow-step">
                        <div class="step-number">2</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <div class="step-title">Household Transmission Studies</div>
                            <div class="step-details">
                                <strong>Case Study:</strong> USA300 MRSA transmission in US households
                                <div class="step-specs">
                                    <strong>Samples:</strong> 146 USA300 strains from Los Angeles and Chicago<br>
                                    <strong>Method:</strong> WGS with phylogenetic analysis<br>
                                    <strong>Results:</strong> Mean 12-17.6 SNPs between family members<br>
                                    <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Continuous transmission within families
                                </div>
                                <p><strong>Key Insight:</strong> Low SNP diversity within households confirms close-contact transmission patterns.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="flow-step">
                        <div class="step-number">3</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <div class="step-title">Antimicrobial Resistance Evolution</div>
                            <div class="step-details">
                                <strong>Case Study:</strong> Daptomycin resistance development
                                <div class="step-specs">
                                    <strong>Key Genes:</strong> rpoB, clpX, mprF mutations<br>
                                    <strong>Mechanism:</strong> Stepwise SNP acquisition under selection pressure<br>
                                    <strong>Method:</strong> Longitudinal WGS of clinical isolates<br>
                                    <strong>Clinical Impact:</strong> Resistance prediction and treatment optimization
                                </div>
                                <p><strong>Key Insight:</strong> SNP tracking reveals resistance evolution pathways, enabling predictive intervention strategies.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="flow-step">
                        <div class="step-number">4</div>
                        <div class="step-content">
                            <div class="step-title">Livestock-Human Transmission</div>
                            <div class="step-details">
                                <strong>Case Study:</strong> ST398 MRSA in companion animals and humans
                                <div class="step-specs">
                                    <strong>Approach:</strong> Comparative genomics of animal and human isolates<br>
                                    <strong>Results:</strong> Interspersed phylogenetic clustering<br>
                                    <strong>Substitution Rate:</strong> ~1.47×10⁻⁶ per nucleotide site per year<br>
                                    <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Bidirectional transmission between species
                                </div>
                                <p><strong>Key Insight:</strong> SNP analysis provides genetic evidence for cross-species transmission, informing One Health approaches.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section" id="section-cutoffs">
                <div class="section-title">SNP Distance Cutoffs for Epidemiological Interpretation</div>
                
                <div class="results-grid">
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">≤25</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">SNPs<br>Recent Transmission<br>(Same Outbreak)</div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">40-60</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">SNPs<br>Possible Transmission<br>(Epidemiologically Linked)</div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="stat-box">
                        <div class="stat-number">>100</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">SNPs<br>Distinct Outbreaks<br>(Unrelated Strains)</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="warning-box">
                    <strong>Important Note:</strong> SNP cutoff values vary by study design, population structure, and time frame. These represent general guidelines that should be validated for specific epidemiological contexts.
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section" id="section-future">
                <div class="section-title">Future Directions and Limitations</div>
                
                <div class="theme-container">
                    <div class="theme-box methodological">
                        <div class="theme-title">Technological Advances</div>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Third-generation sequencing:</strong> Long-read technologies for improved structural variant detection</li>
                            <li><strong>Real-time analysis:</strong> Rapid SNP calling for immediate outbreak response</li>
                            <li><strong>Portable sequencing:</strong> Point-of-care genomics for resource-limited settings</li>
                            <li><strong>Integrated platforms:</strong> Automated sample-to-result workflows</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="theme-box genetic">
                        <div class="theme-title">Current Limitations</div>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Bioinformatics expertise:</strong> Complex analysis requires specialized training</li>
                            <li><strong>Standardization:</strong> Need for consistent protocols and cutoffs</li>
                            <li><strong>Cost considerations:</strong> High-throughput methods still expensive for routine use</li>
                            <li><strong>Data integration:</strong> Combining genomic data with clinical and epidemiological information</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="significance-box">
                    <div class="significance-title">Clinical Significance and Impact</div>
                    <div class="significance-content">
                        This comprehensive review demonstrates that SNP-based methods have revolutionized S. aureus epidemiology and clinical microbiology. The integration of high-resolution genomic data with traditional epidemiological approaches has enhanced our ability to track transmission, monitor resistance evolution, and implement targeted infection control measures. As sequencing costs continue to decrease and bioinformatics tools become more accessible, SNP analysis is becoming an essential component of modern clinical microbiology laboratories.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
